-- China shares close up on strong financials, rare earths  
-- 
-- Fri Apr 04, 2014 03:14AM EDT
-- None



SHANGHAI, April 4 (Reuters) - China shares closed higher on Friday, buoyed by strong financials and a surge in rare earths, as investors speculated in growth in the sector, following surges in the recently opened rare earths exchange.

The Shanghai Composite Index <.SSEC> ended up 0.7 percent at 2,058.83 points. The CSI300 <.CSI300> of the leading Shanghai and Shenzhen A-share listings rose 1 percent. Rare earth stocks posted major gains in the afternoon with China Minmetals Rare Earth Co Ltd <000831.SZ> up 10 percent and Inner Mongolia Baotou Steel Rare-Earth Group Hi-Tech Co Ltd <600111.SS> up 3.8 percent. Banking shares stabilised, with almost all 16 listed banking shares gaining ground. Hua Xia Bank Co, Ltd <600015.SS> was up 1.7 percent and Industrial Bank Co Ltd <601166.SS> gained 2.1 percent on the day. Property also stabilised after several swings deep into positive and negative territory over the past week.  The CSI300 property sub-index <.CSICMREI> gained 0.6 percent, with Hua Yuan Property Co <600743.SS> jumping 6.4 percent and Yeland Group Co <000616.SZ> rising 3.7 percent.